1
00:00:05,680 --> 00:00:06,840
- Kayano-san.
- Hmm?

2
00:00:06,870 --> 00:00:09,870
These two guys we're about to
meet... which one's the bottom?

3
00:00:11,370 --> 00:00:13,216
Yamada, if you dare ask
them that question to their faces,

4
00:00:13,240 --> 00:00:14,880
I'll have you replaced.

5
00:00:15,810 --> 00:00:16,810
Hey...

6
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:21,000
(Day 0)

7
00:00:24,640 --> 00:00:26,640
One hundred days?

8
00:00:27,300 --> 00:00:28,110
That's the idea.

9
00:00:28,111 --> 00:00:30,396
But we won't be following you
and filming for all 100 days.

10
00:00:30,420 --> 00:00:33,960
We'll film your daily life
for the first few days.

11
00:00:33,990 --> 00:00:36,530
After that, the only mandatory
shoot is the final day.

12
00:00:36,620 --> 00:00:37,490
For the rest of the time,

13
00:00:37,491 --> 00:00:39,719
we'll be in touch with you regularly.

14
00:00:39,720 --> 00:00:41,216
We're hoping to capture
your most authentic moments...

15
00:00:41,240 --> 00:00:42,770
Hmph... Authentic moments, huh?

16
00:00:43,580 --> 00:00:45,610
We hope we can.

17
00:00:45,640 --> 00:00:47,070
Oh, right.

18
00:00:51,750 --> 00:00:56,020
My only redeeming quality is that I
never drop crumbs when I eat toast.

19
00:00:56,840 --> 00:00:57,840
Huh?

20
00:01:09,430 --> 00:01:10,480
This project...

21
00:01:10,600 --> 00:01:12,479
Isn't this a bit like false advertising?

22
00:01:12,480 --> 00:01:15,670
Well, it's true we won't
be filming every day.

23
00:01:15,700 --> 00:01:18,439
But we'll be in constant contact with you
during this period.

24
00:01:18,440 --> 00:01:20,520
If anything comes up,
we'll be there to film.

25
00:01:20,620 --> 00:01:22,849
So, to call it a 100-day documentary...

26
00:01:22,850 --> 00:01:24,940
isn't technically a lie.

27
00:01:24,980 --> 00:01:26,460
I see.

28
00:01:26,520 --> 00:01:30,350
So as long as you don't call it "100 days
of non-stop filming," you're in the clear?

29
00:01:31,920 --> 00:01:32,920
You could say that.

30
00:01:34,880 --> 00:01:38,240
I can also finish an iced coffee with a
straw without making a single slurping sound.

31
00:01:38,320 --> 00:01:39,320
Huh?

32
00:01:49,900 --> 00:01:50,900
So...

33
00:01:50,980 --> 00:01:52,959
When does filming start?

34
00:01:52,960 --> 00:01:54,799
We have a deadline, so at the latest...

35
00:01:54,800 --> 00:01:56,180
We can start tomorrow.

36
00:01:56,370 --> 00:01:57,539
Tomorrow?

37
00:01:57,540 --> 00:01:58,410
Yeah.

38
00:01:58,540 --> 00:02:00,580
The sooner we start, the sooner we finish.

39
00:02:00,600 --> 00:02:01,600
Right?

40
00:02:01,850 --> 00:02:04,080
Um... Okay.

41
00:02:04,920 --> 00:02:06,560
Great, it's settled then.

42
00:02:14,420 --> 00:02:19,030
We became well-known after being interviewed
about the partnership oath system.

43
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:21,400
But honestly,

44
00:02:21,430 --> 00:02:23,676
the very fact that we have to be
interviewed for something like this...

45
00:02:23,700 --> 00:02:25,020
is strange in itself.

46
00:02:25,940 --> 00:02:26,940
Yes.

47
00:02:27,740 --> 00:02:29,570
I want this country

48
00:02:30,040 --> 00:02:33,210
to become a place where same-sex couples
can exist as a matter of course.

49
00:02:34,600 --> 00:02:35,600
Not for today,

50
00:02:36,020 --> 00:02:37,209
but for the future.

51
00:02:37,210 --> 00:02:39,050
That's the kind of
documentary I want to make.

52
00:02:42,220 --> 00:02:44,620
Let's create something that
can change the world together.

53
00:02:45,480 --> 00:02:46,480
Okay.

54
00:02:50,300 --> 00:02:52,359
- Thank you for the meal.
- Thank you for the meal.

55
00:02:52,360 --> 00:02:54,360
Do you two have any
plans for the rest of the day?

56
00:02:54,620 --> 00:02:56,059
We were thinking of catching
a movie before heading home.

57
00:02:56,060 --> 00:02:58,070
A date. How nice.

58
00:02:58,600 --> 00:02:59,980
Well, we'll get out of your hair then.

59
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:00,940
Thank you so much for today.

60
00:03:00,941 --> 00:03:02,381
We look forward to working with you.

61
00:03:05,600 --> 00:03:07,280
Hey, what was that all about?

62
00:03:07,480 --> 00:03:08,080
Huh?

63
00:03:08,172 --> 00:03:10,380
Man... I'm exhausted.

64
00:03:11,200 --> 00:03:13,160
Could you at least try
to have a better attitude?

65
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:15,880
I almost burst out laughing.

66
00:03:16,220 --> 00:03:18,380
All that talk about capturing
our "authentic moments."

67
00:03:18,460 --> 00:03:20,490
We broke up ages ago.

68
00:03:20,680 --> 00:03:21,960
"Broke up" is a strong word.

69
00:03:22,020 --> 00:03:23,380
We still live together, after all.

70
00:03:25,440 --> 00:03:27,460
Hey, this...

71
00:03:27,500 --> 00:03:29,800
Oh, aren't you going to the movies?

72
00:03:30,600 --> 00:03:31,979
I'm heading home.

73
00:03:31,980 --> 00:03:33,100
Huh?

74
00:03:41,620 --> 00:03:42,620
What?

75
00:03:43,240 --> 00:03:44,979
So filming starts tomorrow now?

76
00:03:44,980 --> 00:03:46,380
Yeah, that's right.

77
00:03:47,100 --> 00:03:48,529
Are you sure about that?

78
00:03:48,530 --> 00:03:51,260
It's fine. Actually, I'm
pretty fired up about it.

79
00:03:51,720 --> 00:03:53,490
As long as you think it's fine.

80
00:03:56,340 --> 00:03:57,340
But you know,

81
00:03:58,160 --> 00:04:02,600
shouldn't you make a little more time
for your personal life?

82
00:04:02,780 --> 00:04:04,470
Take a page from Naomi's book.

83
00:04:06,440 --> 00:04:07,540
She...

84
00:04:07,970 --> 00:04:11,799
balances everything so well,

85
00:04:11,800 --> 00:04:15,180
both work and her life with her husband.

86
00:04:16,220 --> 00:04:17,220
Right?

87
00:04:17,860 --> 00:04:20,680
- I guess so...
- See?

88
00:04:22,600 --> 00:04:24,380
Your belly's gotten so big.

89
00:04:24,980 --> 00:04:27,520
Well, I could go into labor any day now.

90
00:04:28,660 --> 00:04:31,820
- I'm sorry to bother you at a time like this.
- Not at all.

91
00:04:32,180 --> 00:04:34,919
Kasuga-san is nice, isn't he?

92
00:04:34,920 --> 00:04:35,920
Yes.

93
00:04:36,200 --> 00:04:38,329
What about Hasegawa-san?
What's your impression?

94
00:04:38,330 --> 00:04:42,320
Oh, well...
I do sense a bit of distance between them.

95
00:04:42,780 --> 00:04:44,660
But I'm hoping they'll
warm up to us over time.

96
00:04:46,440 --> 00:04:49,040
I feel that the issues
Kasuga-san and his partner face

97
00:04:49,310 --> 00:04:52,510
are not entirely unrelated to us as women.

98
00:04:53,860 --> 00:04:54,860
I agree.

99
00:04:55,320 --> 00:04:57,019
That's why I want to make a documentary

100
00:04:57,020 --> 00:04:59,180
that not only dispels prejudice
against homosexuality,

101
00:04:59,740 --> 00:05:03,099
but all prejudice related
to gender and sexuality.

102
00:05:03,100 --> 00:05:04,529
That was my thinking

103
00:05:04,530 --> 00:05:06,000
when I proposed this project.

104
00:05:06,780 --> 00:05:08,960
I can certainly feel your passion.

105
00:05:10,060 --> 00:05:12,600
Don't worry, you can count on
me to take over for Naomi-san.

106
00:05:14,440 --> 00:05:15,540
Thank you.

107
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:17,100
I'm looking forward to it.

108
00:05:17,720 --> 00:05:18,820
Yes.

109
00:05:19,060 --> 00:05:20,260
I'll do my best.

110
00:05:27,380 --> 00:05:28,380
I'm home.

111
00:05:29,100 --> 00:05:30,110
Welcome back.

112
00:05:41,340 --> 00:05:42,390
Croquettes?

113
00:05:43,340 --> 00:05:44,340
Yeah.

114
00:05:45,760 --> 00:05:47,360
It's rare to see you frying things.

115
00:05:49,400 --> 00:05:50,500
Do you want some?

116
00:05:50,700 --> 00:05:52,070
I can fry them up if you do.

117
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:03,320
Hey, about dinner...

118
00:06:03,880 --> 00:06:05,520
Let's try to eat together.

119
00:06:06,200 --> 00:06:07,200
Why?

120
00:06:09,850 --> 00:06:10,600
For the shoot.

121
00:06:10,620 --> 00:06:13,690
We need to get that happy couple
vibe back as soon as possible.

122
00:06:15,160 --> 00:06:17,779
Can't we just act the part?

123
00:06:17,780 --> 00:06:19,040
It's not that simple.

124
00:06:21,140 --> 00:06:23,980
The atmosphere today was
pretty awkward, wasn't it?

125
00:06:25,573 --> 00:06:27,313
Okay, okay, I get it.

126
00:06:46,280 --> 00:06:47,760
Should I just chop this?

127
00:06:48,420 --> 00:06:49,689
Oh, no, no.
I'll do it.

128
00:06:49,690 --> 00:06:50,690
It's fine.

129
00:06:51,260 --> 00:06:52,489
It's fine, I've got it.

130
00:06:52,490 --> 00:06:53,809
It's fi...

131
00:06:53,810 --> 00:06:55,000
Ow!

132
00:06:59,220 --> 00:07:00,220
See?

133
00:07:15,200 --> 00:07:16,580
Is this the only kind we have?

134
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:18,050
Stop complaining.

135
00:07:18,700 --> 00:07:20,640
No, I'm not complaining...

136
00:07:35,840 --> 00:07:37,200
That was a total disaster.

137
00:07:38,860 --> 00:07:39,860
Ow.

138
00:07:40,400 --> 00:07:41,470
Hmm?

139
00:07:42,420 --> 00:07:45,279
That pop-up shop... the line was insane.

140
00:07:45,280 --> 00:07:47,010
And in the end, this was all we could get.

141
00:07:50,450 --> 00:07:53,350
But you seemed so happy then.

142
00:07:55,020 --> 00:07:56,560
That's because you looked happy.

143
00:07:56,590 --> 00:07:58,020
Your mood was contagious.

144
00:08:15,010 --> 00:08:15,840
Hey.

145
00:08:15,870 --> 00:08:18,080
The Honey Gourami died.

146
00:08:18,400 --> 00:08:20,410
One of the five we got last week.

147
00:08:21,900 --> 00:08:23,019
What?

148
00:08:23,020 --> 00:08:23,890
Are they all dead?

149
00:08:23,890 --> 00:08:24,890
No.

150
00:08:25,850 --> 00:08:28,050
It looks like... just one died.

151
00:08:32,460 --> 00:08:35,160
Eh, maybe it couldn't handle the heat.

152
00:08:37,930 --> 00:08:38,930
What?

153
00:08:39,360 --> 00:08:41,200
I'm just saying, maybe
the tank was too hot.

154
00:08:42,300 --> 00:08:44,546
Maybe there really are tropical
fish that can't take the heat.

155
00:08:44,570 --> 00:08:46,000
Don't joke about that.

156
00:08:46,040 --> 00:08:47,570
We're talking about a life here.

157
00:09:04,860 --> 00:09:06,790
Where are you going?

158
00:09:07,060 --> 00:09:08,090
For a walk.

159
00:09:54,700 --> 00:10:01,700
"The Boy and I Who Will Breka Up in 100 Days"
(Episode 2)

160
00:10:04,510 --> 00:10:06,996
Are you two the type to have a big appetite
and eat a hearty breakfast in the morning?

161
00:10:07,020 --> 00:10:07,780
(Day 1)
No, not really.

162
00:10:07,780 --> 00:10:08,780
Oh, I see.

163
00:10:20,760 --> 00:10:22,360
- Time to eat.
- Let's eat.

164
00:10:26,840 --> 00:10:27,840
What is it?

165
00:10:28,570 --> 00:10:30,540
Your mouth. You've got some sauce.

166
00:10:33,800 --> 00:10:35,040
No, not there.

167
00:10:37,780 --> 00:10:38,780
Mm.

168
00:10:40,040 --> 00:10:41,880
That's a cute bandage.

169
00:10:42,450 --> 00:10:43,450
Huh?

170
00:10:43,650 --> 00:10:44,650
Oh, no.

171
00:10:45,660 --> 00:10:46,940
It was just the only one we had.

172
00:10:53,860 --> 00:10:56,100
We've been together for
about a year and a half.

173
00:10:56,680 --> 00:10:58,660
We started living together
around the same time.

174
00:11:00,400 --> 00:11:01,639
Oh, I'll get it.

175
00:11:01,640 --> 00:11:02,480
I'll just put this here then.

176
00:11:02,480 --> 00:11:03,480
Okay.

177
00:11:05,220 --> 00:11:06,980
Back then, I got kicked
out of my old place.

178
00:11:08,300 --> 00:11:09,300
I was broke.

179
00:11:11,200 --> 00:11:13,750
And I was forced to quit my job.

180
00:11:14,300 --> 00:11:16,120
Once you come out as gay,

181
00:11:16,150 --> 00:11:18,230
you really run into all
sorts of situations at work.

182
00:11:20,540 --> 00:11:22,220
I wasn't clear enough just now.

183
00:11:22,940 --> 00:11:26,460
Firing someone just for being gay
is illegal, at least.

184
00:11:27,300 --> 00:11:28,500
The reason I quit

185
00:11:29,220 --> 00:11:32,560
was simply because it
was the easier way out.

186
00:11:35,720 --> 00:11:37,980
But it's been great living together.

187
00:11:38,340 --> 00:11:40,610
He has delicious meals
waiting for me when I get home.

188
00:11:40,640 --> 00:11:43,140
He completely won over my stomach.

189
00:11:54,900 --> 00:11:55,900
Oh.

190
00:11:56,640 --> 00:11:59,060
Um... Is this a BL novel?

191
00:11:59,400 --> 00:12:00,400
Oh.

192
00:12:01,140 --> 00:12:03,860
- Yes, it is.
- I actually bought this book myself.

193
00:12:04,460 --> 00:12:06,199
So gay people actually read this stuff?

194
00:12:06,200 --> 00:12:07,200
We do.

195
00:12:08,120 --> 00:12:10,940
In this day and age,
it's harder to avoid it.

196
00:12:11,820 --> 00:12:13,449
Besides, when I was a teenager,

197
00:12:13,450 --> 00:12:15,679
knowing that stories like this existed
was a kind of salvation for me.

198
00:12:15,680 --> 00:12:18,040
- Oh, I see.
- Yeah.

199
00:12:19,330 --> 00:12:21,680
Do you read them too, Hasegawa-san?

200
00:12:22,020 --> 00:12:23,770
Oh, I'm not much of a reader.

201
00:12:25,310 --> 00:12:26,610
I see...

202
00:12:28,590 --> 00:12:29,000
Huh?

203
00:12:29,001 --> 00:12:30,190
Aren't we doing an interview?

204
00:12:30,520 --> 00:12:31,220
Oh.

205
00:12:31,270 --> 00:12:32,270
Sorry about that.

206
00:12:36,890 --> 00:12:40,230
And in order for same-sex
marriage to be legally recognized,

207
00:12:40,690 --> 00:12:43,990
it's necessary for society to
see that same-sex couples exist.

208
00:12:44,290 --> 00:12:45,200
That's also why

209
00:12:45,201 --> 00:12:46,590
we utilized this system.

210
00:12:47,130 --> 00:12:48,439
We want to prove that
if this system exists,

211
00:12:48,440 --> 00:12:51,770
people who need it will use it.

212
00:12:56,510 --> 00:12:57,550
Um...

213
00:13:00,180 --> 00:13:01,479
What he just said isn't entirely true.

214
00:13:01,480 --> 00:13:02,690
Can I make a correction?

215
00:13:05,090 --> 00:13:06,090
What?

216
00:13:06,270 --> 00:13:07,329
Not entirely true?

217
00:13:07,330 --> 00:13:08,330
Yes.

218
00:13:08,770 --> 00:13:09,360
This guy said

219
00:13:09,361 --> 00:13:12,390
that you can't obtain those rights
without same-sex marriage.

220
00:13:12,930 --> 00:13:14,260
But that's not exactly the case.

221
00:13:15,790 --> 00:13:21,570
Things like notarization, adoption,
or voluntary guardianship contracts...

222
00:13:21,600 --> 00:13:23,470
There are actually a
lot of things you can do.

223
00:13:24,410 --> 00:13:28,140
It's true that the process
is a hassle and expensive,

224
00:13:29,040 --> 00:13:31,080
and some protections
aren't comprehensive enough.

225
00:13:32,510 --> 00:13:36,050
So same-sex marriage is definitely
the most straightforward way.

226
00:13:36,420 --> 00:13:38,369
But to say it's the only way...

227
00:13:38,370 --> 00:13:39,450
that's a lie.

228
00:13:40,960 --> 00:13:43,390
Besides, marriage isn't
just about legal rights.

229
00:13:43,830 --> 00:13:45,570
Not that I'm saying they're not needed.

230
00:13:46,610 --> 00:13:48,360
- I see.
- Yes.

231
00:13:48,650 --> 00:13:50,460
Oh, can you please not cut this part out?

232
00:13:51,650 --> 00:13:52,900
I'll do my best.

233
00:13:55,690 --> 00:13:59,690
Something about those two...
they don't really seem like a couple.

234
00:14:00,370 --> 00:14:04,310
You should stop judging people based on
stereotypes of what a couple "should" look like.

235
00:14:05,170 --> 00:14:06,310
Okay, fine.

236
00:14:09,270 --> 00:14:11,050
By the way, Kayano-san, you're into BL?

237
00:14:11,180 --> 00:14:12,030
Is there a problem with that?

238
00:14:12,030 --> 00:14:12,750
Nope.

239
00:14:12,751 --> 00:14:14,826
It's just that you don't seem
interested in romance stories.

240
00:14:14,850 --> 00:14:16,636
I'm just not interested in romance
stories between men and women.

241
00:14:16,660 --> 00:14:18,109
What's the difference?

242
00:14:18,110 --> 00:14:21,259
Gay and straight romance are
completely different, obviously.

243
00:14:21,260 --> 00:14:22,260
Oh.

244
00:14:35,880 --> 00:14:37,010
It's freezing!

245
00:14:43,030 --> 00:14:44,230
Itsuki.

246
00:14:45,950 --> 00:14:47,020
Let's have a debrief.

247
00:14:48,370 --> 00:14:49,490
A debrief?

248
00:14:50,370 --> 00:14:52,120
Point out what we did wrong today.

249
00:14:52,160 --> 00:14:54,030
And use it to improve the next shoot.

250
00:14:55,910 --> 00:14:58,030
Was there something wrong
with our performance today?

251
00:14:58,070 --> 00:14:59,770
I'm saying we could have done better.

252
00:15:01,390 --> 00:15:02,400
Ah...

253
00:15:03,890 --> 00:15:06,870
I get it... You want
us to be more like that.

254
00:15:06,940 --> 00:15:08,740
More couple-like?

255
00:15:09,430 --> 00:15:11,009
Wiping sauce off each other's mouths.

256
00:15:11,010 --> 00:15:12,630
That's what makes us a couple, right?

257
00:15:13,070 --> 00:15:15,249
Emphasizing that we share
chores like washing dishes.

258
00:15:15,250 --> 00:15:17,080
That's what makes us a couple, right?

259
00:15:18,130 --> 00:15:22,420
Got it. Next time, let's just hold
hands through the whole interview.

260
00:15:22,450 --> 00:15:23,930
Maybe that'll be more effective, huh?

261
00:15:28,630 --> 00:15:31,460
No, why did you lie
about not reading books?

262
00:15:31,470 --> 00:15:33,030
That book was clearly yours.

263
00:15:33,350 --> 00:15:35,890
What if our stories don't line up later?

264
00:15:36,700 --> 00:15:38,800
We're literally filming
based on a fake premise.

265
00:15:38,840 --> 00:15:40,139
And now you're telling me not to lie?

266
00:15:40,140 --> 00:15:41,620
Don't you see how ridiculous that is?

267
00:15:42,550 --> 00:15:44,916
And what about you? What was
that during the interview today?

268
00:15:44,940 --> 00:15:46,610
I had to say it that way.

269
00:15:47,390 --> 00:15:49,129
If I said, "There are other ways
besides same-sex marriage,"

270
00:15:49,130 --> 00:15:50,986
or "You can't easily be
fired just for being gay,"

271
00:15:51,010 --> 00:15:53,396
wouldn't the audience just think,
"the current situation is fine as it is"?

272
00:15:53,420 --> 00:15:54,720
It's just a strategy.

273
00:15:59,790 --> 00:16:01,660
That's called lying, isn't it?

274
00:16:04,390 --> 00:16:06,190
And you have the
nerve to tell me not to lie.

275
00:16:06,950 --> 00:16:09,630
From the very beginning, you've
been asking me to lie with you.

276
00:16:30,470 --> 00:16:33,320
- Good morning.
- Morning.

277
00:16:33,344 --> 00:16:34,426
(Day 2)

278
00:16:34,450 --> 00:16:36,010
Good morning.

279
00:16:36,050 --> 00:16:37,110
Good morning.

280
00:16:37,690 --> 00:16:39,629
About him being gay...

281
00:16:39,630 --> 00:16:42,510
He mentioned it during his self-introduction
when he joined the company.

282
00:16:43,070 --> 00:16:44,000
When you first heard that,

283
00:16:44,001 --> 00:16:45,929
were you taken aback at all?

284
00:16:45,930 --> 00:16:47,140
No, not at all.

285
00:16:47,570 --> 00:16:50,170
Our company aims to be
an LGBT-friendly enterprise.

286
00:16:50,190 --> 00:16:52,870
We've implemented a
variety of supportive measures.

287
00:16:53,310 --> 00:16:55,810
For example, same-sex partners
can live together in company housing.

288
00:16:55,830 --> 00:16:56,830
- I see.
- Yes.

289
00:16:56,870 --> 00:16:58,880
So if Kasuga-san wanted to apply,

290
00:16:58,910 --> 00:17:00,549
he could move into the
dorms with Hasegawa-san?

291
00:17:00,550 --> 00:17:02,769
Yes. Since they've
registered their partnership,

292
00:17:02,770 --> 00:17:03,770
they are eligible.

293
00:17:03,920 --> 00:17:07,349
By the way, I'd like to ask, how
well do you know Hasegawa-san?

294
00:17:07,350 --> 00:17:08,350
Oh...

295
00:17:09,630 --> 00:17:11,030
We've met.

296
00:17:11,660 --> 00:17:14,999
Once, I was looking for a place
for a reunion with some college friends,

297
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:17,470
and Kasuga recommended the bar
where his partner works.

298
00:17:17,490 --> 00:17:19,530
- That's when we met.
- Oh, I see.

299
00:17:19,570 --> 00:17:22,309
What was your impression of him then?

300
00:17:22,310 --> 00:17:23,310
Um...

301
00:17:24,790 --> 00:17:27,070
We didn't really talk much then,

302
00:17:27,370 --> 00:17:28,470
so I can't really say.

303
00:17:28,670 --> 00:17:31,050
But I think he's a very handsome guy.

304
00:17:36,210 --> 00:17:37,229
Okay, thank you.

305
00:17:37,230 --> 00:17:38,390
Yes!

306
00:17:38,910 --> 00:17:40,230
He's such a nice guy.

307
00:17:40,990 --> 00:17:44,360
Treating poor young people like us
to pasta.

308
00:17:44,730 --> 00:17:46,230
- Kayano-san.
- Yes?

309
00:17:47,190 --> 00:17:48,389
After today's shoot,

310
00:17:48,390 --> 00:17:50,760
what's your impression of our company?

311
00:17:52,270 --> 00:17:55,270
Um... I think your company
is very progressive.

312
00:17:55,300 --> 00:17:57,570
It's a wonderful company.

313
00:17:58,470 --> 00:18:00,750
Not just in terms of its LGBT initiatives,

314
00:18:01,310 --> 00:18:02,419
but there's also a high
ratio of female employees.

315
00:18:02,420 --> 00:18:04,010
It seems like a great work environment.

316
00:18:05,230 --> 00:18:07,010
Unlike our company, which is all guys.

317
00:18:07,350 --> 00:18:08,150
Oh?

318
00:18:08,230 --> 00:18:10,890
Besides me, there's only one other
female employee at my company.

319
00:18:11,970 --> 00:18:15,520
And the president sometimes
says some pretty outdated things.

320
00:18:16,790 --> 00:18:18,090
Like sexual harassment?

321
00:18:18,370 --> 00:18:19,879
I don't think he means any harm by it,

322
00:18:19,880 --> 00:18:21,440
so I've never really paid it much mind.

323
00:18:23,630 --> 00:18:25,000
You don't have to forgive him.

324
00:18:25,460 --> 00:18:26,500
Huh?

325
00:18:27,700 --> 00:18:31,440
I don't know what exactly you've heard,
Kayano-san,

326
00:18:31,940 --> 00:18:34,970
but if you feel in your
heart that you can't forgive it,

327
00:18:35,240 --> 00:18:36,540
then there's no need to.

328
00:18:37,480 --> 00:18:38,920
I believe that's an undeniable fact.

329
00:18:40,880 --> 00:18:41,880
Okay.

330
00:18:43,260 --> 00:18:45,540
If you feel you can't forgive
it, then you don't have to.

331
00:18:47,190 --> 00:18:48,190
What's wrong?

332
00:18:48,490 --> 00:18:51,160
Nothing. I just thought
that was really well said.

333
00:18:51,720 --> 00:18:54,801
Because all this time, I've forgiven a lot
of things that were actually unforgivable.

334
00:18:55,130 --> 00:18:56,990
But from now on,

335
00:18:57,190 --> 00:18:59,130
I want to take what
you said to heart.

336
00:18:59,160 --> 00:19:01,200
And try not to be so quick to forgive.

337
00:19:03,300 --> 00:19:04,300
Whatever.

338
00:19:06,200 --> 00:19:07,910
Oh, right.

339
00:19:08,440 --> 00:19:11,610
Kasuga, does your partner ever mention me?

340
00:19:11,880 --> 00:19:13,440
- You mean Itsuki?
- Yeah.

341
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:17,750
Because Kayano-san
asked me today if I knew him.

342
00:19:17,880 --> 00:19:20,000
So I was wondering if he'd
said something on his end.

343
00:19:21,590 --> 00:19:23,620
No, I don't think so.

344
00:19:24,260 --> 00:19:26,490
He's not really interested
in other people...

345
00:19:26,890 --> 00:19:28,660
It's more like he just drifts through life.

346
00:19:57,050 --> 00:19:58,050
Oh...

347
00:19:58,650 --> 00:20:00,220
It's Batch-kun.

348
00:20:07,800 --> 00:20:09,980
They put you on a pedestal for a while,

349
00:20:10,700 --> 00:20:13,670
and when they lose interest,
they just toss you aside.

350
00:20:14,380 --> 00:20:16,140
Everyone's so selfish, right?

351
00:20:16,529 --> 00:20:17,369
Yeah.

352
00:20:17,394 --> 00:20:18,874
Everyone's selfish.

353
00:20:19,170 --> 00:20:20,170
Right?

354
00:20:21,240 --> 00:20:22,240
What are you doing?

355
00:20:23,210 --> 00:20:24,210
What?

356
00:20:28,250 --> 00:20:29,250
Huh?

357
00:20:29,600 --> 00:20:32,339
Were you just talking to that figurine?

358
00:20:32,340 --> 00:20:33,619
No, I wasn't.

359
00:20:33,620 --> 00:20:35,460
No, no, no, you were
definitely talking to it.

360
00:20:36,880 --> 00:20:38,779
I was wrong yesterday.

361
00:20:38,780 --> 00:20:39,410
Hm?

362
00:20:39,411 --> 00:20:40,560
I apologize.

363
00:20:41,300 --> 00:20:42,300
Oh.

364
00:20:46,700 --> 00:20:49,470
Telling you not to lie
was strange, I admit.

365
00:20:50,880 --> 00:20:52,970
After all, I'm the one
who asked you to lie.

366
00:20:55,660 --> 00:20:56,660
But...

367
00:20:56,780 --> 00:20:58,280
with that said,

368
00:20:59,450 --> 00:21:01,250
I want to ask you again.

369
00:21:03,680 --> 00:21:05,209
For the sake of this documentary,

370
00:21:05,210 --> 00:21:06,950
I need you to lie more convincingly.

371
00:21:08,680 --> 00:21:11,720
- This documentary is for people like us...
- That's why I agreed to do it.

372
00:21:12,860 --> 00:21:13,860
Huh?

373
00:21:17,160 --> 00:21:18,730
For people like us,

374
00:21:19,120 --> 00:21:21,680
so that when it counts, we
don't have to just suffer in silence.

375
00:21:21,820 --> 00:21:24,770
We have to clearly lay out the rights
we can fight for now, don't we?

376
00:21:27,220 --> 00:21:28,470
But still...

377
00:21:31,740 --> 00:21:32,780
But still what?

378
00:21:34,460 --> 00:21:36,289
I'll play along a little longer.

379
00:21:36,290 --> 00:21:37,930
This little game of house you're playing.

380
00:21:53,480 --> 00:21:54,929
Are you serious?

381
00:21:54,930 --> 00:21:55,969
Serious about what?

382
00:21:55,970 --> 00:21:57,040
Is this how you pour it?

383
00:21:58,320 --> 00:22:00,259
You've been a terrible
pourer your whole life.

384
00:22:00,260 --> 00:22:01,280
Shut up.

385
00:22:10,750 --> 00:22:13,250
Actually... I've been
keeping a secret from you.

386
00:22:13,820 --> 00:22:14,820
What is it?

387
00:22:19,060 --> 00:22:20,820
I can't really hold my liquor.

388
00:22:21,920 --> 00:22:22,920
What?

389
00:22:23,020 --> 00:22:24,020
Huh?

390
00:22:24,220 --> 00:22:25,220
Why?

391
00:22:27,340 --> 00:22:29,519
Didn't you used to go
on and on about whiskey?

392
00:22:29,520 --> 00:22:30,520
Nah.

393
00:22:30,900 --> 00:22:32,740
I was just trying to
act cool in front of you.

394
00:22:33,920 --> 00:22:35,610
Because you like to drink.

395
00:22:36,320 --> 00:22:37,520
That's so lame.

396
00:22:38,620 --> 00:22:40,840
But you fell for me
because of it, didn't you?

397
00:22:44,010 --> 00:22:45,520
I was totally fooled.

398
00:22:47,250 --> 00:22:50,420
Back then, it was so
obvious you were into me.

399
00:22:50,490 --> 00:22:51,650
Don't be ridiculous.

400
00:22:52,320 --> 00:22:53,790
You were the one who liked me first.

401
00:22:59,820 --> 00:23:00,820
Hey.

402
00:23:01,380 --> 00:23:02,480
Tomorrow...

403
00:23:03,060 --> 00:23:04,870
let's eat together.

404
00:23:05,760 --> 00:23:06,760
Yeah.

405
00:23:07,500 --> 00:23:09,770
We should practice to
make our story convincing.

406
00:23:12,007 --> 00:23:13,007
That's not it.

407
00:23:15,100 --> 00:23:17,580
I just... I genuinely want to eat with you.

408
00:23:19,040 --> 00:23:20,240
Tomorrow, and the day after.

409
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:23,200
And every day from now on.

410
00:23:34,400 --> 00:23:35,600
Can we...

411
00:23:37,340 --> 00:23:41,000
start over?

412
00:23:46,060 --> 00:23:47,916
(Next Episode)
I don't want to let those kids down.

413
00:23:47,940 --> 00:23:49,279
(Our Unseen Lies and Truths)
Have you always...

414
00:23:49,280 --> 00:23:50,949
planned on living your
life for other people?

415
00:23:50,950 --> 00:23:52,350
Why don't you just get a job?

416
00:23:52,380 --> 00:23:53,880
You're taking this way too lightly.

417
00:23:54,010 --> 00:23:56,420
I'm not talking about a right.
I'm talking about commitment.

418
00:23:56,450 --> 00:23:58,250
Then just commit to it.

